The Evolution of Law Enforcement Strategy​

3Ts: An evidence-based approach is a systematic method that focuses on identifying what is truly effective in law enforcement. Instead of relying on tradition, habit, or popular opinion (e.g., arresting or patrolling randomly whenever there is a crime), this method uses evidence from empirical studies to make decisions. It is similar to evidence-based medicine, where doctors use results from clinical trials to choose the most effective treatments.​

 The Triple-T Model: This is the core strategic framework of this method, comprising three principles:​

 Targeting: Focusing limited resources on the most harmful types of crime or hotspots.​

 Testing: Testing interventions through scientific trials or evaluations to measure their actual impact, rather than simply assuming they are effective.​

 Tracking: Closely monitoring the implementation and results of law enforcement activities to provide continuous feedback and improvement.​

 Objective: This approach helps overcome the lack of feedback in traditional law enforcement, enabling leaders to design measurable interventions, thereby increasing professionalism and practical impact in wildlife protection​

