1. Phiên bản văn bản đã sửa (Revised Version)​

1. Where to Find Evidence?​

When starting a project, the first step is to find evidence from similar situations that have occurred before. Evidence here refers to "what works and what doesn't" in law enforcement strategies.​

 ​

Main sources of evidence include:​

The Center for Problem-Oriented Policing (POP Center): Located at Arizona State University (USA), this is a vast resource for law enforcement. While largely focused on urban policing, it now includes a "Wilderness Problems" section concentrating on combating wildlife trafficking.​

 ​

The Herman Goldstein Award: This is an archive of case studies from around the world, documenting how agencies have addressed specific law enforcement problems.​

 ​

The George Mason Matrix (Evidence-Based Policing Matrix): A tool that synthesizes over 120 studies in the US, allowing you to look up which methods have proven effective (black dots), ineffective (white dots), or harmful (red triangles).​

 ​

Meta-analysis reports: This is the highest level of evidence, synthesizing results from multiple high-quality studies to draw general conclusions about the effectiveness of a strategy (e.g., hotspot patrolling).​

 ​

For example: If you are facing rhino poaching, you can access the POP Center website to find reports on how reserves in Africa have used technology or community engagement to mitigate this risk.​

 ​

2. How to Create It?​

Because the evidence-based approach is still very new in the field of conservation, it is highly likely that you will not find readily available evidence for your situation. In such cases, you need to create evidence yourself by designing your project in a scientific way.​

 ​

How to create evidence based on the Testing principle in the Triple-T model:​

Minimum standard (Requires a control group): For an activity to be considered "creating evidence," you cannot simply report the numbers before and after implementation. You must have a control group for comparison.​

 ​

Using Randomized Controlled Trials (RCTs): This is the best way to generate strong evidence.​

 ​

Example of how to create evidence:​

Situation: You want to know if installing surveillance cameras reduces animal trapping in the forest.​

Incorrect approach (Does not create reliable evidence): You install cameras in Area A, see a reduction in trapping, and conclude the cameras are effective. In reality, the reduction in trapping may be due to heavy rain preventing hunters from entering the forest, not the cameras.​

The correct approach (Creating evidence): You randomly select 10 similar areas. You install cameras in 5 areas (experimental group) and leave 5 areas unchanged (control group). If, after 6 months, traps are significantly reduced only in the 5 areas with cameras while the other 5 remain unchanged, then you have created valuable empirical evidence that cameras are indeed effective in that context.​

Creating your own evidence through small, self-improving projects will help build a database to enhance future decision-making for the entire law enforcement industry.​

